Day 7 - Claude Model Selection & Reasoning Effort

What I Learned:-

Today I learned that Claude provides different models for different types of tasks.
Choosing the right model and reasoning effort helps improve both output quality and efficiency.

My Profile:-

- B.Tech CSE (AI & ML) Student
- Daily Claude User
- Learning AI and Prompt Engineering
- Interested in Coding, Research, and Career Growth

My Personalized Claude Strategy:-

After analyzing my daily tasks, Claude suggested that Sonnet is the best primary model for me because it offers a balance of speed, intelligence, and cost.

When to Use Haiku:-

- Quick questions
- Fast summaries
- Simple rewrites
- Basic tasks

When to Use Sonnet:-

- Coding help
- Learning concepts
- Prompt engineering
- Daily productivity work
- Project planning

When to Use Opus:-

- Deep research
- Complex reasoning
- Long-term strategy
- Advanced problem solving

Recommended Effort Levels:-

Low:
Simple questions and quick tasks

Standard:
Daily learning, coding, and productivity tasks

High:
Research, project planning, and technical problem solving

Max:
Critical decisions and highly complex tasks

My Daily Workflow:-

- Use Haiku for quick tasks
- Use Sonnet for most daily work
- Use Opus only when deep reasoning is required

Key Learnings:-

1. Different models are designed for different purposes.
2. Using the correct reasoning effort improves results.
3. Sonnet is the best all-around model for my daily needs.
4. Opus should be reserved for complex and research-heavy work.

Conclusion:-

Understanding model selection and reasoning effort helps me use Claude more effectively and get better results while saving time.
